  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Elegy for Minister Geum
  author: Kim Yang-gyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Was your prose alone the five-colored qilin of a blessed age?
    Your zither and chess—even pastimes touched clarity and truth.
    A visitor unmatched at the nine-fold palace gates,
    yet among those who held the chancellorship for ten years, only four are named.

    After you, the pure wind you left becomes a mirror for ten thousand ages.
    The sweet osmanthus in your hand bloomed as spring for countless homes.
    Who would not shed tears in your honor?
    Yet it is your white-haired student whose tears soak through his cloth.
  footnotes:
    - The 'five-colored qilin' references the legendary auspicious beast associated with sage rulers and virtuous officials in Chinese tradition.
    - The 'nine-fold palace gates' refers to the innermost sanctum of imperial power, suggesting Minister Geum's intimate access to the throne.
    - The 'sweet osmanthus' (桂, gye) symbolizes both official rank and virtue in classical East Asian poetry.
    - The final image of the weeping white-haired student evokes the grief of disciples mourning their mentor's passing.
